  <static seed="1442" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations3.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{r+6}{5r+4}} = \frac{5}{12} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{4\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of all fractions in this equation, we multiple all terms with the common denominator. In this equation, the common denominator is <m>{12\mathopen{}\left(5r+4\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{r+6}{5r+4}} \amp = \frac{5}{12} \\
   {\frac{r+6}{5r+4}} \cdot {12\mathopen{}\left(5r+4\right)} \amp = \frac{5}{12} \cdot {12\mathopen{}\left(5r+4\right)} \\
   12(r+6) \amp = 5(5r+4) \\
   12r+72 \amp = 25r+20 \\
   12r+72  \mathbf{-25r-72} \amp = 25r+20 \mathbf{-25r-72}  \\
   -13r \amp = -52 \\
   \frac{-13r}{-13} \amp = \frac{-52}{-13} \\
   r \amp = 4
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>{12\mathopen{}\left(5r+4\right)} \ne 0</m>, or <m>r \ne -\frac{4}{5}</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>r = 4</m>.</p>
</solution>
